---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '@/components/Header.astro';

const title = "The agent-guardrail landscape, 2026";
const date = '2026-05-15';
const description =
  "Lakera is at Cisco now. Protect AI is at Palo Alto. Lasso is independent. Meta open-sourced its own. Here's the actual shape of the market, and why open-source still has a seat at the table.";
---

<Layout title={`${title} — Aojie Yuan`} description={description}>
  <main>
    <Header current="writing" />

    <article>
      <header class="post-head">
        <a href="/writing" class="back">← Writing</a>
        <time datetime={date}>
          {new Date(date).toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' })}
        </time>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="lede">{description}</p>
      </header>

      <section class="prose">
        <p>
          When I started building AEGIS in late 2025, "agent guardrails" was
          still a label most enterprise buyers had to be talked into.
          Eighteen months later, almost every serious infrastructure vendor
          ships some flavor of it, and the consolidation pattern is
          unmistakable. If you're building a product in this category, or
          buying one, here's the lay of the land as I see it from the
          inside.
        </p>

        <h2>Tier 1 — the big-vendor absorptions</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Cisco AI Defense</strong> (which absorbed Lakera in mid-2025)
          and <strong>Palo Alto Prisma AIRS 3.0</strong> (which absorbed Protect AI
          and Portkey across 2025–26) are the two unavoidable names. Both
          ship as part of a larger network security stack, both have real
          enterprise sales motions, and both inherit their parents' ability
          to sell into security teams that have never thought about agents
          before. Lakera Guard's prompt-injection detector, repackaged
          inside Cisco, is probably the highest-volume guardrail running in
          production today.
        </p>

        <p>
          The cost is rigidity. Buying Cisco AI Defense or Prisma AIRS
          means buying into Cisco's or Palo Alto's existing posture about
          how runtime security should look. If your AI product needs to
          enforce a policy these vendors didn't anticipate, you wait for
          a release. There's no fork.
        </p>

        <h2>Tier 2 — the independent SaaS</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Lasso Security</strong>'s recent pivot to "Intent Deputy" —
          per-agent behavioral baselines + drift detection — is the most
          differentiated bet I've seen from the independents. It's
          orthogonal to prompt-injection detection: instead of asking
          "is this call malicious?" Lasso asks "is this call out of
          character for this agent?". For long-lived agents in production,
          that's a real signal.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Galileo</strong> bundles runtime intervention into its
          evaluation platform — the pitch is "the same suite that scored
          your model in CI now blocks it in prod." Strong story for teams
          who buy the eval-first worldview, less compelling for teams who
          treat eval and runtime as separate concerns.
        </p>

        <h2>Tier 3 — open source</h2>

        <p>
          This is where the action is, and where AEGIS lives.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Meta LlamaFirewall</strong> is the most credible
            open-source entrant. PromptGuard&nbsp;2 for jailbreak detection,
            an agent-alignment auditor that inspects chain-of-thought for
            goal divergence, and CodeShield for code-generation safety. The
            framing is "library, not platform" — there's no Cockpit, no
            audit log, no human-in-the-loop. You're meant to glue it into
            your own stack.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>NVIDIA NeMo Guardrails</strong>, especially Colang 2.0,
            is the most expressive: you can write conversational flows,
            multi-step rails, parallel evaluation. It's also the heaviest
            — Colang is a real DSL, and the NeMo runtime expects to live
            inside an NVIDIA-shaped stack.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Guardrails AI</strong> remains the easiest single-call
            input/output validator. Excellent if your problem is
            "structured output validation for one LLM call." Not designed
            for multi-step agents.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Protect AI LLM Guard</strong> is the broadest
            scanner-by-scanner toolkit — 35 individual scanners across
            input and output. The price you pay for breadth is that
            nothing composes; it's a library of detectors, not a system.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where AEGIS fits, and where it doesn't</h2>

        <p>
          The category open-source AEGIS targets isn't "best prompt-
          injection detector" — Lakera and PromptGuard own that already.
          It's "the open-source agent guardrail that ships a UI, an audit
          trail, human approvals, and per-tenant customization in one
          package." LlamaFirewall doesn't ship a Cockpit. NeMo doesn't
          ship a compliance audit log. Guardrails AI doesn't do
          multi-step agents. There's room in the middle.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you're a small company that wants to self-host a complete
          guardrail story — DSL, dashboard, approvals, hash-chained
          traces — you can do it with AEGIS today. If you're a Fortune
          500 that wants someone in Cupertino to take the support call,
          you buy Cisco AI Defense.
        </p>

        <p>
          Both are reasonable choices. The thing the market doesn't have
          yet — and probably won't for a while — is an open-source
          guardrail that's <em>also</em> the obvious choice for that
          Fortune 500.
        </p>

        <h2>What I'd watch in 2026</h2>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Agent-alignment auditing</strong> moving from research
            (LlamaFirewall's chain-of-thought inspector) into the default
            stack. Most guardrails today check the call; few check the
            agent's reasoning that produced it.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Per-tenant adaptive learning.</strong> Lasso's Intent
            Deputy is the early shape. The interesting question is whether
            customers will tolerate "your model gets better the longer it
            sees your traffic" without it feeling like surveillance.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The MCP attack surface.</strong> Model Context Protocol
            adoption made MCP servers the new "everything is reachable
            from one place" target. Cisco AI Defense already inspects MCP
            traffic; I expect every guardrail to follow.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>

  <style>
    main {
      max-width: 640px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 1.5rem 1.75rem 6rem;
    }
    .post-head {
      margin: 4rem 0 3rem;
    }
    .back {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      border-bottom-color: transparent;
      display: inline-block;
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
    }
    .back:hover {
      color: var(--text);
      border-bottom-color: var(--text);
    }
    .post-head time {
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem);
      line-height: 1.15;
      margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
      letter-spacing: -0.014em;
    }
    .lede {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      max-width: 46ch;
      line-height: 1.55;
      margin: 0;
    }
    .prose {
      font-size: 1.04rem;
      line-height: 1.72;
    }
    .prose h2 {
      font-size: 1.55rem;
      margin: 3rem 0 1rem;
      line-height: 1.3;
    }
    .prose p {
      margin: 0 0 1.3rem;
    }
    .prose ul {
      padding-left: 1.3rem;
      margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
    }
    .prose li {
      margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    }
    .prose code {
      background: var(--surface);
      padding: 0.1rem 0.4rem;
      border-radius: 3px;
      font-size: 0.86em;
      border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    }
    .prose em {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--accent);
    }
    .prose strong {
      font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--text);
    }
  </style>
</Layout>
